article.headline: Phoenix snaps six-game skid
article.linkText: Suns get first win without Marbury
article.story: PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The Phoenix Suns finally rang in 2004. After six straight losses kept them winless in the new year, the Suns beat the Portland Trail Blazers 105-96 Thursday night. Amare Stoudemire had 22 points and 10 rebounds to give Phoenix just their fourth road win this season. "This was huge, man," said Shawn Marion, who added 21 points and eight rebounds. "This is out first win of the new year, so it felt good." The Suns had lost six straight and were 0-4 since the trade that sent Stephon Marbury and Anfernee Hardaway to the New York Knicks. But with 55 percent shooting, they were able to take advantage of the Blazers, coming off a 1-4 road trip. The Blazers, who have lost 15 of 17 on the road but were a favorable 14-5 at the Rose Garden before Thursday, were without forward Rasheed Wallace, who sat out his fourth straight game with a strained left ankle as trade rumors continued to swirl about him. Stoudemire was playing in his just third game since missing 18 with a high ankle sprain. "I'm playing my game. This is my game. It's all I live for," Stoudemire said. "I love to play basketball." The Suns went up by as many as 14 points in the second half. Howard Eisley, acquired by Phoenix in the Marbury deal, hit a 20-foot jumper to make it 80-66. The Blazers cut it to 88-84 on Wesley Person's 3-pointer midway through the fourth quarter. It was as close as they would get. "If we can get some wins and they start coming, the guys are really going to start to believe in what we're doing," Suns coach Mike D'Antoni. Zach Randolph led the Blazers with 21 points and 12 rebounds, his 21st double-double of the season. With Wallace out and Derek Anderson showing some of last season's spark, the Blazers tooled with their starting lineup. Anderson started in just his fifth game back after missing the start of the season with back trouble. Jeff McInnis, who had started in the backcourt with Damon Stoudamire recently, came off the bench. Second-year forward Qyntel Woods started in place of Wallace, who was in uniform on the bench but did not play. Wallace continues to be the subject of several trade rumors. The Suns took an early 19-9 lead on Stoudemire's turnaround jumper. After Casey Jacobsen's 3-pointer put Phoenix ahead 35-22, Portland center Vladamir Stepania missed two free throws, and the home team was loudly booed. The Blazers responded with 10-point run capped by Randolph's jumper to make it 35-32. The Suns took over again when Leandro Barbosa's fast-break layup made it 49-38, and Phoenix went on to lead 56-47 at halftime. Blazers coach Maurice Cheeks said perhaps some of the trade rumors had started to take a toll on his team. "You could see it in the first half. It was like we were running in the mud," Cheeks said. "It's not as though we didn't try but it was as if things were on our mind."< ^NOTES:@ The Blazers activated forward Travis Outlaw and center Ruben Boumtje-Boumtje before the game. Outlaw had tendinitis in both knees and Boumtje Boumtje had a strained left ankle. ... The Suns had 12 fast-break points in the first half, while the Blazers had none. ... It was Randolph's 23rd game with 20 or more points.
